               <label>Name in local variety (in transcription)</label>
               <name xml:lang="ara-x-DMG">Mādaba</name>
            </head>
            <div type="positioning">
               <p>
                  <geo>31°42'N 35°47'E</geo>
                  <country>Jordan</country>
               </p>
            </div>

            <div type="typology">
               <p rend="typology">East (Mashreq) › Levant › Jordan › Centre</p>
               <p>Rural sedentary dialect with strong Bedouin influences (bəgūl-type).</p>
            </div>

            <div type="general">
               <p>Mādabā is located in the Balqāʔ province of Jordan some 33 km southwest of the capital ʕAmmān. The city has a population of about 60,000 and is famous for its Byzantine and Umayyad mosaics. The present inhabitants are mostly Christians whose ancestors immigrated from Karak in the 19th century. The dialect of Mādabā belongs to the <hi rendition="i"> </hi>group of the Jordanian dialects.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p>There are no comprehensive grammatical studies on the dialect of Mādabā. The existing studies date back to the 1960s and focus on texts, providing only basic information on grammatical features.</p>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:TUV9WXF7">Czapkiewicz (1960)</rs> is a selection
               of nine ethnographic texts and 45 sayings with a German translation.
               It includes information on customs and traditions, houses and occupations, and
               is accompanied by a 12-page grammatical sketch of the so-called Balgāwī-dialects.
               <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:9JFJG7LP">Hamarne (1963)</rs> is a collection of
               ethnographic texts describing children’s songs and games. <rs type="bibl" ref="PHNBQ29N">Palva
               (1969)</rs> consists of twelve short texts, mainly folk tales and anecdotes,
               followed by three pages of grammatical notes. The speakers of these
               texts are all Greek Orthodox Christians.</p>
            </div>
         </div>
